And ...\
\
Note 1: The first thing we have to know is that a data structure creates a new type: Once a data structure is declared, a new type with the identifier specified as structure_name is created and can be used in the rest of the program as if it was any other type.\

\fs24 \

\b\fs32 Example:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf5 struct\cf0  product \{\
  \cf5 int\cf0  weight;\
  \cf5 float\cf0  price;\
\} ;\
\
product apple;\
product banana, melon;\
\
\cf5 struct\cf0  product \{\
  \cf5 int\cf0  weight;\
  \cf5 float\cf0  price;\
\} apple, banana, melon;\
\
\pard\pardeftab720

\f0\fs28 \cf0 Note 2: Once we have declared the sets of valid identifiers for objects of a determined structure type, we can operate directly with their members. To do that we use a dot (.) inserted between the object name and the member name.\
\

\b\fs32 Example:
\b0\fs28 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720

\f2\fs24 \cf0 apple.weight\
apple.price\
banana.weight\
banana.price\
melon.weight\
melon.price\
\
